tweet.text:
<tweet 0 start>: Here's how to create better CTA's in just 3 steps.

1. Use clear action oriented language as your button labels.

Instead of vague labels such as "Click here", "Get Started", "Learn More", consider stronger and more clear labels such as "Sign up for a 30 day free trial", "Download My Free eBook", "Discover Our Latest Offers".

2. Make CTA's visually stand out

Use colours that contrast against the background and pop out, demanding the user's attention. An accent colour that aligns with your brand is oftentimes perfect for your CTA's.

3. Leverage microcopy below the CTA to further incentivise users to push the button

- Use copy and badges that demonstrate social proof ("rated 4.9 by 200+ people on TrustPilot")
- Use guarantees ("30-day money-back guarantee")
- Use copy that creates urgency ("offer valid only for the next 24 hours")<tweet 0 end>

Here are some key factors to consider:

- How do you embed a seamless UI?

- How do you unify the agent‚Äôs state and actions with the app?

This is where I would like to introduce CoAgents by @CopilotKit, they offer all the essential building blocks for full-stack agentic apps.

The best part, they're completely open-source with an MIT Licence ‚ú®

tweet.text:
<tweet 0 start>: How I grow with clients long term?

Here's what works for me:

1. Stay relevant to evolving needs
Make their success your priority. As the business get traction, more work follows. Keep your skills relevant to their changing design needs. It‚Äôs win-win.

2. Adapt to their style
Each client is different. I stay flexible with how we communicate, workflow and process. It doesn't matter, as long as it works. You can optimise along the way.

3. Lean on your expertise
They hire me for more than just skills. I have specific industry knowledge in edtech, startups, B2B SaaS etc. I can spot patterns with similar work. I share my insights beyond design. As a design partner, I act like one.

4. Be human
Don't make it transactional. Build rapport and just talk normally. Be transparent if life happens. Once trust is built, the real value of a long-term relationship kicks in.

5. Build a network of trusted partners
When clients scale, they need engineers, marketers, copywriters and more. If they trust you, they will ask for referrals. A good referral boosts your credibility and what you can offer.

‚éØ

I‚Äôm always looking to expand my network. Are you a founder, fractional, or similar? Say hi.<tweet 0 end>

profile.name: Bryan Johnson /dd
profile.biography: Conquering death will be humanity‚Äôs greatest achievement.

tweet.text:
<tweet 0 start>: We recently launched a Blueprint biological age test. It measures your speed of aging and the age of eleven critical organs. 

I've personally been using this test for years as it's grown from interesting to up-and-coming. It's tracked accurately with my other biomarker tests and has offered new insights that other tests miss.  I think I've completed more of these tests than anyone in the world. 

If you're interested in biological age tests, here is a breakdown of how they came to be, and what distinguishes each generation. 

1st Generation (Horvath, Hannum): created from data sets on people at different chronological ages (single snapshot). predicts chronological age accurately, not strongly correlated to health and longevity outcomes

2nd Generation (GrimAge PhenoAge): created from data on different people (single snapshot) and trained beyond predicting chronological age to predict health biomarkers and mortality risk. 

3rd Generation (DunedinPACE): the first to track the aging outcomes of participants across their lifespan based on data from the same individuals from the age 3 to age 51. This is the technology we use. 

Advantages of DunedinPACE: 
1. Rules out noise in the data due to environmental exposures resulting from people living though different times and in various places.

2. Instead of reporting biological age, or time to death, DunedinPACE reports the speed of aging which makes it very responsive to interventions and ideal for evaluating them with minimal lag and turnover time.

3. Experimentally, DunedinPACE has been shown as the best predictor of mortality, and age related decline compared to earlier clocks.

4. In a recent evaluation of 16 biological aging clocks across 51 interventional studies, DUNEDIN Pace stood out as most reliable by always being either in agreement with a majority of the remaining clocks, or uniquely detecting a change in biological age, where no other clock did.<tweet 0 end>

tweet.text:
<tweet 0 start>: Hard truth about the dev -> solopreneur path

Your first biz won't be great (unless you get lucky).

But that's ok and here's why.

As a career enterprise developer, I had to re-learn MVPs:

- Email vendor: SendGrid
- Newsletter vendor: Kit, but Beehiiv looks ü§å
- Where to host: Hetzner
- What tech stack: Go (I'm allergic to JS/TS)
- What libraries to use: htmx, templ, echo, ent, goth
- How to handle auth: Just do SSO
- Which database: SQLite btw
- Data warehouse: Clickhouse but also ‚ù§Ô∏è duckdb
- Local dev env: Overmind + pre-push hook instead of CICD
- Payment processor: Stripe, but keep üëÄ on Polar
- Message queue: NATS Jetstream

Did I waste time?

No, because your first project has one goal:

To make your second go faster.

I don't need to learn as much the next time. I have examples I can steal.

P.S.

If you want a Go-based MVP starter kit, DM me. I have one open-sourced.<tweet 0 end>

profile.biography: Nick Cosentino | Simplifying software engineering concepts for you | Principal Software Engineering Manager @Microsoft | Creator of @BrandGhostAI üëª

tweet.text:
<tweet 0 start>: The secret to becoming a better programmer:

Just like any other skill we want to improve: Practice!

Programming is no different.

Just watching tutorials or reading articles won't cut it. Those resources are great, but they won't make you an expert on their own.

To TRULY improve, we need to put in the work. Repetition is essential.

And that means getting stuck and unstuck when solving problems. Over. And over.

That's where the learning happens.

We can ENHANCE our practice with: 
- Books 
- Articles 
- Videos 
- Courses 

My recommendation is to focus on building things.

If you think, 'That sounds too hard!' remember to break it down into manageable parts. Eventually, you'll find a piece you can tackle.

- Focus on that smaller task.
- Start building it out.
- Get stuck on it.
- Use resources.

Then, move on to the next challenge. Repeat this process. 

I've been following this approach for years, and it still works for me for learning.

#SoftwareEngineering #Coding #Programming<tweet 0 end>

profile.biography: hi. figuring out the next thing. tinkering. looking for other ppl in sf to hack with.

tweet.text:
<tweet 0 start>: hey everyone!

been a while.

6-months actually...

i took a one-way flight out of sf with no plan.
didn't know if i'd ever even come back.

ended up spending time in some of the most peaceful places on the entire planet.

from the villages of morocco to the remote forests of the czech republic to the peaceful outskirts of islamabad.

i listened to the beatles a lot
spent most days doing nothing
met some wise people on the road!

it was really, really cool.

but...you don't just get on a plane and have your problems disappear (would be nice)

when the company ended there was an overflow support from fans, friends, and investors:
"it was a good run. you gave it your best"

but of course, you are always your worst critic.

for the majority of my travels i just felt sad, tired, confused, everything at once.

i felt like a flop. like maybe i really did burn out. maybe this was really it. maybe the story ends here.

i think what freaked me most was the thought that i‚Äôd never feel that love building stuff ever again. as if this spark i'd had since i was 13 was just gone forever.

that was the worst.

but, i think time just did what time does.
as of today
i feel happier than ever.
and more excited than ever.

i feel like while on the road, i found that light again.

i feel like that kid within me, the kid that see's the world as brand new and just wants to make cool things...i feel like i found him again.

it was a journey. one day i‚Äôll tell the whole story.

(and no, i did not take acid lol)

as of now i'm back in sf, i live 5m away from the office, and i'm just falling in love with making things again.

i really feel 13 again.

and, i feel like i'm ready to build something really fucking cool again. i‚Äôm not done yet.

thank you to everyone reading this who still cares. it means a lot.

and, thank you to the thousands of you who messaged me and tagged me over the last 6-mo checking in on me or just sending a note of appreciation.

even though i didn't have it in me to reply... it meant more than you'll ever know!

p.s: im actively hacking on new ideas everyday. if you're in sf and maybe wanna work together, hmu! we can meet up.<tweet 0 end>

tweet.text:
<tweet 0 start>: B2B online distribution isn‚Äôt just about platforms or methods, it‚Äôs about people too. Companies should encourage their employees to build their personal brands.

The problem? Most try to position their product before positioning themselves. Social media presence is a clear example for this. 

It‚Äôs not about gathering thousands of followers, not engaging by sending endless connection requests, or only posting a product image, "this is where I work" update, etc. once in a month or year.

That‚Äôs not personal branding, it‚Äôs just broadcasting.

True personal branding, when aligned with company branding, means employees have already chosen a niche that resonates with the company‚Äôs industry.

It‚Äôs not turning employees into corporate influencers, it‚Äôs ensuring their professional identity naturally supports the company‚Äôs mission.

Of course, hiring someone doesn't mean hiring their social media. Not talking about the company's social media support group on WhatsApp, or forcing people to support toxic company posts.

This alignment should come from the roots:

- What is the company‚Äôs mission and vision?
- What are the employees' long-term career goals?
- Are their future dreams aligned?

Now we're talking about both marketing and hiring.

Most B2B companies, 99.9% of them-I think, don't understand the importance of this but there is a huge opportunity in B2B online sales for those that do.

And companies that resist this change will lose their key employees to those embrace it.

tweet.text:
<tweet 0 start>: Too much of my life has been in fight or flight

I've used work to avoid grief

I'm terrified of failure

And I've adopted perfectionist tendencies as a way to exert control

Sometimes these feelings have served me

They help me to keep pushing when others would give up

Force me to take risks

And drive action day after day

But I'm stuck

Something I've noticed since we hit $55,000 MRR...

My logical brain tells me I can make changes in my life to be happier right now

To live in a way that's free of my past

But my habits and body won't stop "push" mode

It's a lifelong pattern that's hard to break

But living driven by my pain and trauma isn't actually living

And it's definitely not freedom

So I have a choice - to slow down, enjoy my achievements, and actually live today

Or keep pushing and seeking validation and self-worth through MRR

It's time for me to live

That means

- No more arbitrary revenue goals that don't serve me
- Sharing to give, not to prove my worth
- Slowing down so I can choose to stay slow or speed up
- Starting every day peacefully, no phone, no social media
- Training for strength 3x a week
- Trying a 4-day working week, leaving space for adventure 
- Spending my work day living my value of craft

This change is terrifying for me and I can feel a deep internal resistance even as I write these words

But I'm curious to try and see what happens

Does anyone else identify with these feelings?

[Attached some notes I wrote after my most recent therapy session]<tweet 0 end>

tweet.text:
<tweet 0 start>: New Zealand is so, so, so nice!

My wife and I have been here for 3 weeks and we already want to move.

Nature is stunning. There are sheep everywhere. It's quiet AF and the air is pure (PM2.5 <3¬µg/m¬≥ everywhere).

You can surf, ski, mountain bike, trail, or hike pretty much anywhere. It's a little paradise if you like outdoor activities. Next to my Airbnb, there's a 6-meter bridge and I can jump in the river after work. This is life.

People are kind and open. I'm not a small-talk person but people make it so normal so I've talked to lots of people! Maybe it's like that in the US/Canada too?

New Zealand produces a lot of food like milk, vegetables, and berries. It's easy to find delicious, organic, and healthy food.

My wife & I are looking for a new home after Bali. We rarely have a crush on a place. But New Zealand feels special.

Flip side:
- Entrepreneur ecosystem is absent (we're South)
- It's far from everything<tweet 0 end>

tweet.text:
<tweet 0 start>: The Equation of Extremes: How Outlier Icons Benefit the Center

Imagine society as a vast mathematical formula where every action and idea contributes to an overall balance. In this grand equation, figures like @elonmusk and Kanye West are the statistical outliers: the extremum points that, at first glance, seem to push our collective data toward the fringes. Yet, their radical statements and performances actually benefit those in the center.

Why do these extreme antics help moderate voices rather than polarize opinions further? The answer lies in our nature as social animals. We inherently crave belonging and are reluctant to stand out too starkly. When someone like Musk or Kanye makes a bold, uncompromising statement, it often repels those who prefer the comfort of subtlety. Their flamboyant behavior forces most of us to retreat toward the center, where social acceptance and balance reside.

In mathematical terms, these outliers act as a corrective force. Just as an extremum in a function temporarily stretches the curve before the system naturally re-centers itself, the shock value of extreme performances pushes people away from the fringes and back toward moderation. Rather than deepening societal divisions, their unpredictable acts highlight the appeal of the center.

This concept -¬†what I might call –∞ "balanced impartiality"¬†- is a sound principle for navigating today‚Äôs polarized world. By inadvertently recalibrating the social spectrum, the bold moves of figures like Musk and Kanye remind us that the middle ground is a dynamic nexus where stability thrive.<tweet 0 end>

profile.name: Mihiro Suzuki
profile.biography: going bananas

tweet.text:
<tweet 0 start>: Fridges in asian convenience stores are not actually refrigerators. I always wondered why I could eat ‚Äúcold‚Äù good tasting onigiri in Japan.

Its because the temperature is actually set to 60F, with a one day ‚Äúfridge‚Äù lifespan.

Week 26 of Running Experiments to Test Ideas

This week I dove into restaurant marketing, wholesale foods, and premium products.

Japanese restaurant consulting gig learnings
- Revenue drivers were 2-3 main items on the menu
- Marketing should be simple. Their messaging was confusing. Consumers should associate you for some specific product, and the rest are ancillary 

The problem with onigiri at scale
- Fridge temp. Temps in asia are around 60F while its around 40F in America. Thats why the rice doesn‚Äôt get hard in Japan.
- Distribution reliance. Distributors will take 30-40% of your product. This kills profitability. You need some sort of leverage when going into the deal or have super good margins.
- Plastic. Plastic wrappers make things look very nice. But it isn't too good to be using it. But it's a problem to be addressed at scale because its way to expensive in the beginning. 
- Customer volume and personas. You have to make so many and the customers are less understanding of the issues you face.

Sell to a small, high paying demographic -> target larger demographic range at scale
- In the beginning, I won‚Äôt have much resources to serve a lot of people. Plus the demographic will be more understanding of pricing, issues, and have a strong network. 
- Ultimately I want to take on wholesale generic food distribution. Generic sandwiches and salads are so gross.

Premium product ideas
- Omakase bento box. Pop up style omakase with bento box to take experience home
- Mochi. Mochi ice cream or just pure mochi.
- Soba/Udon. Handmade Soba and Udon. There isn't a place in Austin that sells that yet and has decent margins/preservability<tweet 0 end>

tweet.text:
<tweet 0 start>: How much do you teach your child about financials?

My older kids are now in 5th grade, so I thought it a good time to introduce them to our stock portfolio. They know where to track it (on my phone, with my supervision, obviously, because these days all apps have one-touch buy! üò±), know what kind of stocks to buy (industry you know, uptrending, uptrending fast vs uptrending slow, what do the indexes show, etc), and are the first to know when I just bought or sold or rebalanced our portfolio.

Anyway, today I was doing just that (rebalancing) and with a slip of a finger (goddamn one-touch-buy apps) I bought more stocks of one kind than I wanted.

So, today I'm going to explain to my kids about covered calls. ü§∑‚Äç‚ôÄÔ∏è

In the end, the goal is to get them familiar enough with the terms so that when I'm no longer around, they can manage this or their portfolio more or less knowledgeably. It took me a long while to learn and if I had known about stocks and options as a child it would've been much easier and I would've started investing sooner, which, after all, is what makes the biggest difference. ü•∞<tweet 0 end>

<tweet 0 start>: It's funny but building a really good "AI Wrapper" is quite hard

Even from pure performance basis

AIs constantly get nerfed. What used to be working just fine 1month ago - fails now

Some AIs are exceptionally good at following the prompt
Others at giving diverse answers
Others at just passing the "vibe check"

If you really do want to bring the best AI experience to your app, you most probably need to use several models from several providers

I think I spent at least a few days each month re-evaluating the results and seeing how I can make them better, what other model I can use for some specific task, or where I could adjust the prompt

Constant fight<tweet 0 end>

 Let‚Äôs get absurd. Ever hear of the Monty Python ‚ÄúKiller Joke‚Äù sketch? It‚Äôs about a joke so hilarious it kills anyone who hears it. Pure fiction, right? Well, almost. There‚Äôs a condition called fatal hilarity‚Äîrare cases where people have laughed so hard they triggered heart attacks or asphyxiated. In 1975, a British man named Alex Mitchell reportedly died laughing at a TV show called The Goodies. The skit? A kilted Scotsman fighting a black pudding with bagpipes. His widow even thanked the show for making his last moments joyful. Dark, deep, and absurdly funny.

tweet.text:
<tweet 0 start>: I was going to just post this picture of plant stands I made but it ended up as tips to avoid burnout üëá

I'm heading to Ireland/UK in a few days for my first full day off in months.

I feel like I can keep going but I do notice some signs that have led to burnout before. Silly mistakes, lack of appetite, and increased blood pressure are a few.

It's been a good streak and finding better ways to weave in life and keep up the intensity. Here are some habits that are working well for me and may work for you also:

- Morning workouts while listening to audiobooks 

Start the day with a different perspective while increasing your energy capacity. This is a non-negotiable for me.

- 2 daily walks

After lunch and after dinner to help digestion, get fresh air, relax eyes, move body, and catch up with my wife/talk about nonsense, or the meaning of life.

- Make it easy to eat healthy

Meal prep, snack prep, shopping prep. The difference in energy levels and brain clarity are huge going from junk to healthy foods.

- Enjoy your work

Easier said than done, I know. But if you get excited about your work and do so while talking about it, you can also inspire others and become an energy fountain. 

- Take intentional screen breaks

Rest your eyes and brain in set breaks by holding a plank, stretching your spine by hanging, timed chore challenges, or working on a hobby for a little bit.

One of my hobbies recently has been woodwork as I thought it was fitting as there's a lot of wood in Canada. Oh yeah, here's that picture of some plant stands I made:

tweet.text:
<tweet 0 start>: DeepSeek R1 was just the start‚Äîthis new Chinese research from @Kimi_Moonshot lets RAG AI agents devour entire codebases and documentation with no context limits.

Mixture of Experts and Sparse attention make near-infinite context possible.

üßµ1/n

üìå Challenge of Long-Context Attention

Transformers still face heavy computational loads when sequences become extremely large. The default attention pattern compares every token with every other token, creating costs that scale quadratically. This overhead becomes problematic when reading entire codebases, multi-chapter documents, or large legal texts.

üìåMixture of Block Attention (MoBA)

MoBA applies Mixture of Experts ideas to attention. The model divides input sequences into blocks, then a trainable gating function computes an affinity score between each query token and each block. Only the highest-scoring blocks get used in the attention, which removes the need to attend to every token in the full sequence.

Blocks are defined by segmenting the sequence into equal spans. Each query looks at a pooled representation of the keys in each block (for example, by mean-pooling), ranks their importance, and picks a few blocks for detailed attention. The block that contains the query is always included. A causal mask ensures tokens never see future information, preserving left-to-right generation.

üìåSeamless Switch between Sparse and Full Attention

MoBA replaces normal attention without changing parameter counts. It remains compatible with standard Transformer interfaces, so it can switch between sparse and full attention in different layers or during different training phases. Some layers might keep full attention for specialized tasks (like supervised fine-tuning) while most layers use MoBA to cut costs.

üìå This fits into a larger Transformer stack by replacing standard attention calls. The gating ensures each query focuses on a manageable subset of blocks. Causality is handled by filtering out blocks in the future and by applying local masks within the query‚Äôs current block.

üìå The below figure shows queries being routed to only a few ‚Äúexpert‚Äù blocks of keys/values instead of the entire sequence. The gating mechanism assigns each query to the most relevant blocks, which cuts attention computations from quadratic to sub-quadratic.

üìå The gating mechanism computes a relevance score between each query and a condensed representation of each block. It then picks the top‚Äëk blocks for every query, regardless of how far away those blocks are in the sequence.

Because each query only processes a few blocks, the computation remains sub‚Äëquadratic, yet the model can still jump to distant tokens if the gating scores indicate high relevance.<tweet 0 end>

tweet.text:
<tweet 0 start>: This is the biggest waste of time ever. 

You can literally get stuck for days if working with a large code base. I've been there, it's not a good place to be.

Here's what i started doing to mitigate that:

1 - Always review the code that AI is modifying. Treat it like a PR review, don't be lazy, if you hire a developer you will review their PRs, you should do the same with AI.

2 - Let AI work on smaller tasks, break one generic prompt into multiple smaller prompts.

3 - Commit your code after every successful change for damage control.

4 - If one model is not working for a specific prompt, try switching to different models even if the other model is usually dumber.

5 - Don't forget that you are a developer, code the critical parts yourself.<tweet 0 end>

tweet.text:
<tweet 0 start>: If you can survive college, you can survive anything.

You walk into college thinking you have it all figured out.

First year? You still believe -
‚Ä¢ Good grades = good job.
‚Ä¢ Friendships last forever.
‚Ä¢ Life will be smooth.

Then, reality slaps you.

 ‚Äî You apply for so called clubs, internships, committees‚Äîrejected, rejected, rejected

‚Äî You realize no one cares if you show up. No spoon-feeding. No hand-holding. It‚Äôs all on you.

And that‚Äôs when college does its real job,
it stops protecting you.

By second year, you start adapting.

‚Äî You learn survival. All-nighters, last-minute assignments, bargaining with auto walas like pro or travelling through local buses.

‚Äî You understand failure. Rejections don‚Äôt break you anymore. You take the L and move on.

‚Äî You find real friendships. Not built on convenience, but on ‚Äúbro, send me the notes‚Äù at 1:30 AM.

‚Äî You stop waiting for life to get easier. Because it never does. Instead, you get better.

By the time you graduate, you‚Äôre not the same person who walked in.

‚Ä¢ You‚Äôve been broke, lost, rejected.
‚Ä¢ You‚Äôve doubted yourself, struggled, almost given up.
‚Ä¢ But you‚Äôve also figured things out, built resilience, and come out stronger.

College doesn‚Äôt just give you a degree.

It throws you into chaos, watches you struggle, and then somehow, you make it through.

And that‚Äôs when you realize‚Ä¶

You‚Äôre unbreakable.<tweet 0 end>

tweet.text:
<tweet 0 start>: Wondering how blind (or visually impaired) people play cricket? Here's a short explanation:

1. Both teams have the same number of players as regular teams (11 on each side).

2. Players are classified into three categories based on their level of visual impairment:
   - B1: Totally blind
   - B2: Partially sighted
   - B3: Partially sighted with better vision than B2(highest level of partial sight allowed).

Team Composition - Teams have 11 players total
->4 players must be B1 (totally blind)
->3 players must be B2 (partially blind)
->4 players must be B3 (partially sighted)

This classification system helps ensure fair competition by grouping players with similar levels of visual impairment

3. When a totally blind player is bowling, they wait for the wicketkeeper (the player standing behind the batsman/striker) to give an audio signal by saying "here-here-here." The blind bowler then throws the ball in the direction of the sound.

4. If a totally blind player (B1) scores 1 run, it is counted as 2 runs.

5. Each team plays for 20 overs. 1 over has 6 throws, so every team get a chance of max 120 strikes. It takes around 90min for one side to complete batting. 

see this attached demo video.  @blind_cricket @VistaCenterNews<tweet 0 end>

<tweet 0 start>: How to test your SaaS homepage copy‚Äôs clarity

1. Ask five to seven people separately for their first impressions. Keep it simple: ‚ÄúWhat do you think my product does?‚Äù or ‚ÄúWho do you think this is for?‚Äù

2. Time their response. If they can articulate your UVP in 10 seconds, your messaging is likely clear.

3. Look for consistency. If most answers are similar, your homepage is doing its job. If responses vary widely, your messaging is vague and needs refining.

Pro tip:

Test with people outside your industry. If a layperson gets it, your target audience definitely will.<tweet 0 end>

<tweet 0 start>: What you work with breaks down

Here's what a fitness trainer who became a world champion bodybuilder at age 51 told about his sore joints, ligament damage and his other injuries.

His idea was simple - what you work, you break.

- Miners have sore lungs and bones
- Truckers have back problems.
- Singers have torn ligaments and broken voices.
- Lawyers often have heart problems and alcohol problems.

The question remains - what breaks down in IT professionals?

What breaks down, of course, is the psyche.

Depression, anxiety, ADHD, stress, burnout - it's all about IT and online jobs.

Every second person has mood problems.

Some are on antidepressants, some drink, and some blow.

Take care of yourself.

Don't take on too much, move more.

tweet.text:
<tweet 0 start>: It‚Äôs interesting that many people still believe Chinese Shu Pu-erh tea is stored underground, with fish, or other absurd myths.

In reality, Shu Pu-erh is simply artificially fermented Sheng Pu-erh. The prepared Sheng Pu-erh leaves are piled into large heaps and generously sprayed with water. Then, they are gathered into mounds where the fermentation process begins.

The tea starts to ‚Äúferment,‚Äù creating a compost-like heat pocket inside the heap, reaching temperatures of around 80¬∞C.

Every week or two, the heap is loosened, sprayed with water again, and reshaped into a mound. This process continues until the tea master decides that the raw material has reached the perfect condition.

For Sheng Pu-erh to naturally age and transform into Shu Pu-erh, it would take at least 30-50 years.

To help more people learn about this, we‚Äôve added a tea fermentation station to our game Tea Farm @teafarmtown 

Soon, we‚Äôll also introduce a mini-game for manually packing tea from these fermentation piles!<tweet 0 end>

tweet.text:
<tweet 0 start>: You are staring at the biggest wave of your life, it's called AI. You either try to  ride it and you might live and flourish, or foolishly run the other way, and it will certainly catch up and kill you.

The cool thing about AI is that we can build stuff that we weren't able to build before, and you don't need permission to start.

Here is what you can do:

1/ If you have too much self-belief to the point of delusion (good). Use reasoning models as a cofounder to help you build:

- Things humanity gave up on. Like large scale architectural wonders, inspiring monuments and statues. Think the colossus of Rhodes, the hanging gardens of Babylon, Sagrada Familia.

- Robotic surgeries: Imagine being the person that solved surgeries. AI-guided precision, zero fatigue, no room for human error.

- Biotech: AlphaFold solved protein folding. Applications of this will change humanity. Organ regeneration and age reversal might work.

- Compete with boom supersonic. Make a faster plane or something.

- Build vertical robots. If Tesla bots and Figure are the ChatGPT of robotics, then go and build the Cursor of robotics.

2/ If you want to build something to achieve financial freedom, bootstrap a vertical AI agent saas (or join a team doing that):

Pick an industry with high-value, repetitive workflows (legal, healthcare, finance, logistics).

Fine-tune existing models with domain-specific knowledge to create an AI agent that automates a critical task 10x better than a human.

Charge high-ticket b2b pricing (not $10/mo consumer AI tools).

You can do the same for video/image models (ex: build something that hollywood needs on top of sora)

Examples are: cursor, lovable, harvey, chatbase, eleven labs, photoai, aragon.

The point is you just need to do something with AI, the only bad move is not moving. 

Imagine staring at the largest wave you will ever see in your life, knowing it will only come once, then running the other way.<tweet 0 end>

tweet.text:
<tweet 0 start>: Monetization vs. Investments: Can You Raise Serious Investment at the Pre-Revenue Stage Today?

Duolingo operated without monetization for four years. The team focused solely on user retention and relied on investments to sustain itself.

Product Hunt followed a similar path. For the first four years, Ryan Hoover attracted investors and users, and when asked about monetization, he responded with something like:
‚ÄúWe have hypotheses, and we‚Äôre working on them.‚Äù

After four years, they launched ads. Later, they experimented with SaaS (which didn‚Äôt work out), and in the last two years, they experienced significant growth with an ad-based model.

Why Were Duolingo and Product Hunt Able to Do This?

üü¢ Duolingo secured funding because:

1Ô∏è‚É£ Luis von Ahn was a successful entrepreneur ‚Äî his previous project, reCAPTCHA, was acquired by Google. Investors love founders who have built big success stories before.
2Ô∏è‚É£ Innovative business model ‚Äî venture investors believed Duolingo could generate revenue without forcing users to pay directly.

üü† Product Hunt attracted investment because:

1Ô∏è‚É£ Ryan Hoover was an active member of the startup community. He had strong connections with well-known entrepreneurs and investors from Y Combinator, AngelList, and other VC networks.
2Ô∏è‚É£ Strong organic growth. Product Hunt quickly gained popularity among founders and investors because it solved a real problem‚Äîhelping startups find early users and receive feedback.
3Ô∏è‚É£ Network effect. The more startups listed their products, the more investors and users joined the platform, creating a self-sustaining growth loop.

In both cases, investors understood:

If a project is growing fast, it can be monetized later, once it reaches a critical mass of users. Monetization too early could slow down growth.

But Can the Same Strategy Work Today?

During our customer development calls with funds that invest at the pre-seed and seed stages, we ask about their key selection criteria.
Every single one of them says they are not interested in pre-revenue startups. You might get $50K to test marketing‚Äîbut nothing more.

To secure a substantial investment, you need:
‚úÖ A warm connection with the investor.
‚úÖ An impressive track record with past successful cases.
‚úÖ A strong Founder-Market Fit.

In all other cases: attract users and generate revenue.<tweet 0 end>

<tweet 0 start>: If you can‚Äôt find the motivation, try this. 

Zoom in. 

It‚Äôs easy to get paralyzed thinking omg how am I going to build a following of 1.45 million on X and Youtube. 

And how am I going to find, develop, and market a product that makes 400k a month. 

Instead ask yourself 3 questions  - 

1. What micro action can I take right now?

2. What is the simplest and shittiest version of that action? 

3. How can I start a rough draft right now? 

It‚Äôs helped me build momentum.<tweet 0 end>
